00:46:09.300 --> 00:46:10.610
We have quarterly meetings.

00:46:10.610 --> 00:46:12.040
Like, OK, you really
want to do this?

00:46:12.040 --> 00:46:12.870
You can do this, but
then you have to

00:46:12.870 --> 00:46:14.420
stop doing these things.

00:46:14.420 --> 00:46:16.590
And I get all angsty and try
and figure out what I

00:46:16.590 --> 00:46:17.660
want to work on.

00:46:17.660 --> 00:46:22.050
But then once we have the idea
we know we're working on, I'm

00:46:22.050 --> 00:46:24.220
very fortunate, in that I get
up in the morning, I look at

00:46:24.220 --> 00:46:26.140
my calendar, and the projects
are blocked out.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:27.260
You're working on this, you're
working on this, you're

00:46:27.260 --> 00:46:28.160
working on this.

00:46:28.160 --> 00:46:31.380
So that's something I'm bad at,
and she's very good at, so

00:46:31.380 --> 00:46:33.680
that works out really
well for us.

00:46:33.680 --> 00:46:35.950
The ideas come from--

00:46:35.950 --> 00:46:38.480
I really am a big
fan of science.

00:46:38.480 --> 00:46:42.410
Not a scientist, but I read
as many blogs as I can.

00:46:42.410 --> 00:46:45.270
And "New Scientist," it's hard
to go through one issue of

00:46:45.270 --> 00:46:48.000
"New Scientist" without taking
notes on four or five

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:49.220
different new projects.

00:46:49.220 --> 00:46:50.730
Because biology is
mesmerizing.

00:46:50.730 --> 00:46:52.650
All the amazing things
that we do.

00:46:52.650 --> 00:46:56.450
And then hacking biology is a
big one for me, not so much in

00:46:56.450 --> 00:46:59.250
the computer sciences, but
every time I see somebody

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:01.630
tweak a genome or do
something, I'm

00:47:01.630 --> 00:47:03.100
like, that's great.

00:47:03.100 --> 00:47:04.220
Let's do that.

00:47:04.220 --> 00:47:07.170
So a lot of times, that
idea will stick.

00:47:07.170 --> 00:47:12.010
Like let's insert this
particular genome into humans

00:47:12.010 --> 00:47:14.470
so that they produce this
particular hormone, which

00:47:14.470 --> 00:47:16.500
defeats this particular
symptom they are

00:47:16.500 --> 00:47:18.160
suffering of lupus.

00:47:18.160 --> 00:47:18.790
Let's do that.

00:47:18.790 --> 00:47:21.110
Which that's worked into
"Pandemic," by the way, so

00:47:21.110 --> 00:47:23.840
this is a case study.

00:47:23.840 --> 00:47:26.000
And that will just sit there.

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:27.780
But that's not a good enough
story on its own, because

00:47:27.780 --> 00:47:29.660
there's no drama,
there's no arc.

00:47:29.660 --> 00:47:32.600
And then like for "Ancestor,"
I learn about the organ

00:47:32.600 --> 00:47:34.810
shortage, and that sticks.

00:47:34.810 --> 00:47:36.790
And then I learn about chimeras,
which is where you

00:47:36.790 --> 00:47:39.740
are taking genetic information
from one animal, one or more

00:47:39.740 --> 00:47:41.470
animals, and putting them
into another animal.

00:47:41.470 --> 00:47:42.950
You wind up with a chimera.

00:47:42.950 --> 00:47:45.420
And thinking that well, wait a
minute, what if we were to do

00:47:45.420 --> 00:47:46.630
all of these things?

00:47:46.630 --> 00:47:48.090
We could have organs.

00:47:48.090 --> 00:47:51.605
And then you learn about
endogenous retroviruses, that

00:47:51.605 --> 00:47:54.690
are viruses that are kind
of stuck in your genome.

00:47:54.690 --> 00:47:56.640
And if you start messing with
this stuff, well, these things

00:47:56.640 --> 00:47:59.970
come out and you get a crazy
bird flu and everyone dies.

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:01.610
That's something they're
actually concerned about.

00:48:01.610 --> 00:48:02.920
I don't really get how
all that works.

00:48:02.920 --> 00:48:05.680
I just know everyone dying
is a good plot point.

00:48:05.680 --> 00:48:07.820
[LAUGHTER]

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:10.310
When I say everyone can die, you
are going to pull the book

00:48:10.310 --> 00:48:11.800
a little bit closer, right?

00:48:11.800 --> 00:48:12.980
So I got that.

00:48:12.980 --> 00:48:15.140
And then I learned about--

00:48:15.140 --> 00:48:16.720
so all these things
stick in the head.

00:48:16.720 --> 00:48:20.030
And then I learned about the
work of, I think, Blair

00:48:20.030 --> 00:48:24.180
Hodges, I believe is his name,
who did a genetic analysis of

00:48:24.180 --> 00:48:28.120
all mammalia and figured out
that the main branches

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:31.750
branched off well before the
extinction event that kind of

00:48:31.750 --> 00:48:33.760
cleared the dinosaurs and
cleared the field for mammals

00:48:33.760 --> 00:48:34.890
to take over.

00:48:34.890 --> 00:48:37.320
There had always been this
premise that it's this one

00:48:37.320 --> 00:48:39.750
ancestor of all of us, and then
the dinosaurs went away,

00:48:39.750 --> 00:48:42.560
and then it went through rapid
expansion into all the

00:48:42.560 --> 00:48:43.420
available niches.

00:48:43.420 --> 00:48:44.380
But it's not.

00:48:44.380 --> 00:48:46.980
The main branch of mammalia
were already there.

00:48:46.980 --> 00:48:49.150
So like, there were tiny little
hippos, and they were

00:48:49.150 --> 00:48:52.370
hiding just like the
tiny little shrews.

00:48:52.370 --> 00:48:53.950
And then all of that
came together.

00:48:53.950 --> 00:48:57.970
I'm like, OK, so what if they
do this genetic sequencing,

00:48:57.970 --> 00:49:01.620
get the genome of everything,
get rid of all the original--

00:49:01.620 --> 00:49:03.910
like if this gene is only
found in tigers,

00:49:03.910 --> 00:49:05.190
we'll remove that.

00:49:05.190 --> 00:49:07.780
And if you remove everything
that's unique and take

00:49:07.780 --> 00:49:10.470
everything that's common, you
basically have the original

00:49:10.470 --> 00:49:12.730
genome of the ancestor
of all mammals.

00:49:12.730 --> 00:49:13.560
So what if we do that?

00:49:13.560 --> 00:49:16.020
Then what if we genetically
sequence that, put in the

00:49:16.020 --> 00:49:19.000
computer, so we can do evolution
on the computer.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:20.080
And then what if
we tweak that?

00:49:20.080 --> 00:49:22.930
OK, now what if we're going to
tweak that in order to make a

00:49:22.930 --> 00:49:26.430
new animal that is going to have
human harvestable organs?

00:49:26.430 --> 00:49:27.830
But we know it's clean.

00:49:27.830 --> 00:49:29.770
There's no retroviruses
in there, because

00:49:29.770 --> 00:49:30.650
we can control it.

00:49:30.650 --> 00:49:32.620
We can see that in the genome.

00:49:32.620 --> 00:49:34.840
So now we've got this perfectly
clean animal.

00:49:34.840 --> 00:49:37.060
It's going to solve the organ
shortage problem.

00:49:37.060 --> 00:49:38.130
And then we're going
to be doing this.

00:49:38.130 --> 00:49:39.800
And then I discover
this great--

00:49:39.800 --> 00:49:41.230
I think it's an [INAUDIBLE]
machine--

00:49:41.230 --> 00:49:44.180
I'm not sure-- that actually
prints proteins.

00:49:44.180 --> 00:49:45.770
And you can print
custom proteins

00:49:45.770 --> 00:49:46.480
right from your computer.

00:49:46.480 --> 00:49:47.580
I'm like, OK, we'll bring
that together.

00:49:47.580 --> 00:49:50.850
Let's just jazz this up so it
can actually print a full

00:49:50.850 --> 00:49:51.710
chromosome.

00:49:51.710 --> 00:49:52.560
Now I can do that.

00:49:52.560 --> 00:49:53.640
There's my hand waving.

00:49:53.640 --> 00:49:58.580
And then all of a sudden,
you've got this animal.

00:49:58.580 --> 00:50:00.260
What are we going to
put this animal in?

00:50:00.260 --> 00:50:04.950
Well, then I learned about the
efforts to bring back the ibex

00:50:04.950 --> 00:50:07.450
or various extinct animals,
where they will

00:50:07.450 --> 00:50:08.600
take a close relative.

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:11.060
I think they tried to do this
with a species of buffalo.

00:50:11.060 --> 00:50:14.140
They enucleate the egg of a cow,
pull out the cow genome

00:50:14.140 --> 00:50:17.210
in the egg, and they take this
genome they've cloned, stick

00:50:17.210 --> 00:50:18.740
it in there, and stick it
right back in the cow.

00:50:18.740 --> 00:50:21.730
Because since it's got the egg
protein coating, the cow

00:50:21.730 --> 00:50:23.620
should recognize as self.

00:50:23.620 --> 00:50:25.420
And hopefully, it'll be able
to gestate in there, a

00:50:25.420 --> 00:50:26.440
C-section will pull it out.

00:50:26.440 --> 00:50:27.370
And they've actually
done this.

00:50:27.370 --> 00:50:29.910
They've actually brought back
extinct animals by letting

00:50:29.910 --> 00:50:32.140
them gestate inside
a close relative.

00:50:32.140 --> 00:50:34.835
So all that trashed--

00:50:34.835 --> 00:50:36.000
INTERVIEWER: Extremely
simple process.

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:36.290
SCOTT SIGLER: Yeah.

00:50:36.290 --> 00:50:37.278
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:37.278 --> 00:50:38.760
AUDIENCE: I understand
what she does now.

00:50:38.760 --> 00:50:40.740
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:40.740 --> 00:50:44.610
SCOTT SIGLER: All of that crams
together to make the

00:50:44.610 --> 00:50:50.050
novel "Ancestor." And then, of
course, science goes horribly

00:50:50.050 --> 00:50:51.690
wrong, and then you get to have
a lot of fun from there.

00:50:51.690 --> 00:50:54.040
They don't know the genome
that they're controlling.

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:57.260
And you get giant 650-pound pack
predators with Dimetrodon

00:50:57.260 --> 00:50:58.380
sails on the back
of your head.

00:50:58.380 --> 00:51:00.020
And it's wicked fun.

00:51:00.020 --> 00:51:00.910
It's so fun.

00:51:00.910 --> 00:51:02.030
It's a fun book.

00:51:02.030 --> 00:51:05.950
So that's how that process--
once you get those ideas, and

00:51:05.950 --> 00:51:08.800
I get all excited, and call A,
and be like, we gotta do this

00:51:08.800 --> 00:51:09.970
one, we gotta do this one.

00:51:09.970 --> 00:51:11.400
Then you start to
outline them.

00:51:11.400 --> 00:51:14.660
Then I take my layman's
knowledge of science and do my

00:51:14.660 --> 00:51:18.150
research, and I hammer out
a really strict outline.

00:51:18.150 --> 00:51:22.450
And then a benefit from giving
crap away free for seven years

00:51:22.450 --> 00:51:25.020
is a lot of scientists--

00:51:25.020 --> 00:51:27.880
and policemen, and firemen,
and soldiers--

00:51:27.880 --> 00:51:31.700
have emailed me to say, I can
tell you're trying to get what

00:51:31.700 --> 00:51:34.410
we do right, and that
matters to us.

00:51:34.410 --> 00:51:37.200
So if you ever need
help, call me up.

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:40.090
I'm a biology Ph.D.
At Harvard.

00:51:40.090 --> 00:51:40.790
Call me any time.

00:51:40.790 --> 00:51:41.630
You're like, awesome.

00:51:41.630 --> 00:51:42.980
Put that in the Rolodex.

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:45.550
So now I've got this amazing
battery of people who are

00:51:45.550 --> 00:51:49.110
experts in their fields, and
I send them the outline.

00:51:49.110 --> 00:51:52.280
They will go through the outline
and say, OK, you've

00:51:52.280 --> 00:51:53.360
kind of got the idea.

00:51:53.360 --> 00:51:55.170
But this could never happen,
and here's why this could

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:55.760
never happen.

00:51:55.760 --> 00:51:56.670
Try this instead.

00:51:56.670 --> 00:51:59.320
Take that back, cobble together
another outline.

00:51:59.320 --> 00:52:00.590
Write the first draft.

00:52:00.590 --> 00:52:03.480
First draft is a real
pain in the ass.

00:52:03.480 --> 00:52:05.300
Because you're writing--

00:52:05.300 --> 00:52:08.360
I'm long-winded, as you
can tell, right?

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:11.600
All of this goes onto
the page as well.

00:52:11.600 --> 00:52:14.600
Then I'll write the first draft,
turn that back over to

00:52:14.600 --> 00:52:17.050
the scientists and the soldiers
and the cops, and

00:52:17.050 --> 00:52:17.840
have them go through it.

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:19.860
And they just tear it apart.

00:52:19.860 --> 00:52:23.600
It's really not a fun part of
the process to know that this

00:52:23.600 --> 00:52:25.580
plot thread that you fell in
love with, and literally spent

00:52:25.580 --> 00:52:27.630
a week of your life, every day,
working on it to get it

00:52:27.630 --> 00:52:29.290
just right, it's
just got to go.

00:52:29.290 --> 00:52:31.220
It just flat-out doesn't work.

00:52:31.220 --> 00:52:32.880
Then they give me
the feedback.

00:52:32.880 --> 00:52:33.800
I go from there.

00:52:33.800 --> 00:52:35.390
And then by the second draft,
things are pretty

00:52:35.390 --> 00:52:36.130
much blocked out.

00:52:36.130 --> 00:52:38.030
And then we go through the
regular draft process with the

00:52:38.030 --> 00:52:39.396
editor at Crown.

00:52:39.396 --> 00:52:40.660
That's how we do it.

